{"title":"Towards Universal Fake Image Detectors that Generalize Across Generative Models","domain":"CV","seeds":[{"problem":"Deep real-vs-fake classifiers trained on images from one generator family (e.g., GANs) fail to generalize to unseen families like diffusion and autoregressive models; they latch onto model-specific low-level artifacts so the real class becomes a sink and diffusion fakes are often predicted as real.","method":"Perform detection without learning task-specific features by classifying in a frozen, task-agnostic feature space from a large pretrained vision-language model. Concretely, embed images with a frozen CLIP ViT-L/14 visual encoder and use cosine-distance nearest neighbor against real/fake feature banks built from a single generator’s data. This avoids overfitting to one model’s fingerprints and yields strong cross-family generalization, improving over the SoTA [49] by about +15.05 mAP and +25.90% accuracy on unseen diffusion and autoregressive models, and even outperforming an oracle-threshold baseline."},{"problem":"Nearest-neighbor over large feature banks can be memory-intensive; a lightweight detector is desirable while preserving universal generalization across generator families.","method":"Freeze the CLIP ViT-L/14 backbone and train only a single linear layer (logistic head) for real-vs-fake (linear probing). This retains the benefits of task-agnostic features with a few hundred trainable parameters, is compute/memory friendly, and matches or exceeds nearest neighbor generalization. It improves over [49] by +19.49 mAP and +23.39% accuracy on unseen diffusion/autoregressive models."},{"problem":"It is unclear which feature spaces and data recipes make fake-image detectors generalize across unseen generator families.","method":"Ablations show that internet-scale, caption-supervised CLIP features are crucial: CLIP visual encoders (especially ViT-L/14) separate real/fake far better than ImageNet-pretrained backbones. The approach generalizes regardless of the training fake source (GAN or diffusion), even cross-family (e.g., training on LDM data generalizes to GANs with large mAP gains), and remains robust to reduced training-set size and nearest-neighbor k. These findings provide practical guidance on backbone choice and data requirements for universal fake detection."}]}
